[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path from a given source node to every other node.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be used to find the shortest path to a specific destination node, by terminating the algorithm after determining the shortest path to that node.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the nodes of the graph represent cities, and the costs of edges represent the distances between pairs of cities connected by a direct road, then Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest route between one city and all other cities.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A common application of shortest path algorithms is network routing protocols, most notably IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) and OSPF (Open Shortest Path First).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It is also employed as a subroutine in algorithms such as Johnson's algorithm.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm uses a min-priority queue data structure for selecting the shortest paths known so far.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Before more advanced priority queue structures were discovered, Dijkstra's original algorithm ran in $\Theta (|V|^{2})$ time, where $|V|$ is the number of nodes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Fredman & Tarjan 1984 proposed a Fibonacci heap priority queue to optimize the running time complexity to $\Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ , where $|E|$ is the number of edges.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is asymptotically the fastest known single-source shortest-path algorithm for arbitrary directed graphs with unbounded non-negative weights.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, specialized cases (such as bounded/integer weights, directed acyclic graphs etc.) can be improved further.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If preprocessing is allowed, algorithms such as contraction hierarchies can be up to seven orders of magnitude faster.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is commonly used on graphs where the edge weights are positive integers or real numbers.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be generalized to any graph where the edge weights are partially ordered, provided the subsequent labels (a subsequent label is produced when traversing an edge) are monotonically non-decreasing.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In many fields, particularly artificial intelligence, Dijkstra's algorithm or a variant offers a uniform cost search and is formulated as an instance of the more general idea of best-first search.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] — Edsger Dijkstra, in an interview with Philip L.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra thought about the shortest path problem while working as a programmer at the Mathematical Center in Amsterdam in 1956.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He wanted to demonstrate the capabilities of the new ARMAC computer.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] His objective was to choose a problem and a computer solution that non-computing people could understand.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He designed the shortest path algorithm and later implemented it for ARMAC for a slightly simplified transportation map of 64 cities in the Netherlands (he limited it to 64, so that 6 bits would be sufficient to encode the city number).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A year later, he came across another problem advanced by hardware engineers working on the institute's next computer: minimize the amount of wire needed to connect the pins on the machine's back panel.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As a solution, he re-discovered Prim's minimal spanning tree algorithm (known earlier to Jarník, and also rediscovered by Prim).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra published the algorithm in 1959, two years after Prim and 29 years after Jarník.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm requires a starting node, and computes the shortest distance from that starting node to each other node.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assign to every node a distance from start value: for the starting node, it is zero, and for all other nodes, it is infinity, since initially no path is known to these nodes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] During execution, the distance of a node *N* is the length of the shortest path discovered so far between the starting node and *N*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the unvisited set, select the current node to be the one with the smallest (finite) distance; initially, this is the starting node (distance zero).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the unvisited set is empty, or contains only nodes with infinite distance (which are unreachable), then the algorithm terminates by skipping to step 6.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the only concern is the path to a target node, the algorithm terminates once the current node is the target node.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the current node, consider all of its unvisited neighbors and update their distances through the current node; compare the newly calculated distance to the one currently assigned to the neighbor and assign the smaller one to it.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the current node *A* is marked with a distance of 6, and the edge connecting it with its neighbor *B* has length 2, then the distance to *B* through *A* is 6 + 2 = 8.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If B was previously marked with a distance greater than 8, then update it to 8 (the path to B through A is shorter).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Otherwise, keep its current distance (the path to B through A is not the shortest).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After considering all of the current node's unvisited neighbors, the current node is removed from the unvisited set.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Thus a visited node is never rechecked, which is correct because the distance recorded on the current node is minimal (as ensured in step 3), and thus final.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once the loop exits (steps 3–5), every visited node contains its shortest distance from the starting node.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The shortest path between two intersections on a city map can be found by this algorithm using pencil and paper.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every intersection is listed on a separate line: one is the starting point and is labeled (given a distance of) 0.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every other intersection is initially labeled with a distance of infinity.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is done to note that no path to these intersections has yet been established.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At each iteration one intersection becomes the current intersection.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the first iteration, this is the starting point.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the current intersection, the distance to every neighbor (directly-connected) intersection is assessed by summing the label (value) of the current intersection and the distance to the neighbor and then relabeling the neighbor with the lesser of that sum and the neighbor's existing label.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] I.e., the neighbor is relabeled if the path to it through the current intersection is shorter than previously assessed paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If so, mark the road to the neighbor with an arrow pointing to it, and erase any other arrow that points to it.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After the distances to each of the current intersection's neighbors have been assessed, the current intersection is marked as visited.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The unvisited intersection with the smallest label becomes the current intersection and the process repeats until all nodes with labels less than the destination's label have been visited.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once no unvisited nodes remain with a label smaller than the destination's label, the remaining arrows show the shortest path.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following pseudocode, dist is an array that contains the current distances from the *source* to other vertices, i.e. dist[*u*] is the current distance from the source to the vertex *u*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The prev array contains pointers to previous-hop nodes on the shortest path from source to the given vertex (equivalently, it is the *next-hop* on the path *from* the given vertex *to* the source).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The code u ← vertex in *Q* with min dist[u], searches for the vertex *u* in the vertex set *Q* that has the least dist[*u*] value.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph.Distance(*u*,*v*) returns the length of the edge joining (i.e. the distance between) the two neighbor-nodes *u* and *v*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The variable *alt* on line 14 is the length of the path from the *source* node to the neighbor node *v* if it were to go through *u*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If this path is shorter than the current shortest path recorded for *v*, then the distance of *v* is updated to *alt*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To find the shortest path between vertices *source* and *target*, the search terminates after line 10 if *u* = *target*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Now sequence *S* is the list of vertices constituting one of the shortest paths from *source* to *target*, or the empty sequence if no path exists.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A more general problem is to find all the shortest paths between *source* and *target* (there might be several of the same length).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then instead of storing only a single node in each entry of prev[] all nodes satisfying the relaxation condition can be stored.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if both *r* and *source* connect to *target* and they lie on different shortest paths through *target* (because the edge cost is the same in both cases), then both *r* and *source* are added to prev[*target*].
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When the algorithm completes, prev[] data structure describes a graph that is a subset of the original graph with some edges removed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its key property is that if the algorithm was run with some starting node, then every path from that node to any other node in the new graph is the shortest path between those nodes graph, and all paths of that length from the original graph are present in the new graph.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then to actually find all these shortest paths between two given nodes, a path finding algorithm on the new graph, such as depth-first search would work.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A min-priority queue is an abstract data type that provides 3 basic operations: add_with_priority(), decrease_priority() and extract_min().
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As mentioned earlier, using such a data structure can lead to faster computing times than using a basic queue.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Notably, Fibonacci heap or Brodal queue offer optimal implementations for those 3 operations.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Instead of filling the priority queue with all nodes in the initialization phase, it is possible to initialize it to contain only *source*; then, inside the `**if** *alt* < dist[*v*]` block, the decrease_priority() becomes an add_with_priority() operation.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Yet another alternative is to add nodes unconditionally to the priority queue and to instead check after extraction (`*u* ← *Q*.extract_min()`) that it isn't revisiting, or that no shorter connection was found yet in the `if alt < dist[v]` block.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This can be done by additionally extracting the associated priority `*p*` from the queue and only processing further `**if** *p* == dist[*u*]` inside the `**while** *Q* is not empty` loop.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] These alternatives can use entirely array-based priority queues without decrease-key functionality, which have been found to achieve even faster computing times in practice.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, the difference in performance was found to be narrower for denser graphs.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To prove the correctness of Dijkstra's algorithm, mathematical induction can be used on the number of visited nodes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The base case is when there is just one visited node, source.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its distance is defined to be zero, which is the shortest distance, since negative weights are not allowed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assuming that the hypothesis holds for k visited nodes, to show it holds for $k+1$ nodes, let u be the next visited node, i.e. the node with minimum `dist[u]`.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The claim is that `dist[u]` is the shortest distance from source to u.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If a shorter path were available, then this shorter path either contains another unvisited node or not.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For all other visited nodes v, the `dist[v]` is already known to be the shortest distance from source, because of the inductive hypothesis, and these values are unchanged.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After processing u, it is still true that for each unvisited node w, `dist[w]` is the shortest distance from source to w using visited nodes only.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Any shorter path that did not use u, would already have been found, and if a shorter path used u it would have been updated when processing u.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After all nodes are visited, the shortest path from source to any node v consists only of visited nodes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Therefore, `dist[v]` is the shortest distance.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Bounds of the running time of Dijkstra's algorithm on a graph with edges E and vertices V can be expressed as a function of the number of edges, denoted $|E|$ , and the number of vertices, denoted $|V|$ , using big-O notation.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The complexity bound depends mainly on the data structure used to represent the set Q.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following, upper bounds can be simplified because $|E|$ is $O(|V|^{2})$ for any simple graph, but that simplification disregards the fact that in some problems, other upper bounds on $|E|$ may hold.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] where $T_{\mathrm {dk} }$ and $T_{\mathrm {em} }$ are the complexities of the *decrease-key* and *extract-minimum* operations in Q, respectively.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The simplest version of Dijkstra's algorithm stores the vertex set Q as a linked list or array, and edges as an adjacency list or matrix.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In this case, extract-minimum is simply a linear search through all vertices in Q, so the running time is ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|^{2})=\Theta (|V|^{2})}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To perform decrease-key steps in a binary heap efficiently, it is necessary to use an auxiliary data structure that maps each vertex to its position in the heap, and to update this structure as the priority queue Q changes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] With a self-balancing binary search tree or binary heap, the algorithm requires ${\textstyle \Theta ((|E|+|V|)\log |V|)}$ time in the worst case; for connected graphs this time bound can be simplified to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The Fibonacci heap improves this to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In common presentations of Dijkstra's algorithm, initially all nodes are entered into the priority queue.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is, however, not necessary: the algorithm can start with a priority queue that contains only one item, and insert new items as they are discovered (instead of doing a decrease-key, check whether the key is in the queue; if it is, decrease its key, otherwise insert it).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This variant has the same worst-case bounds as the common variant, but maintains a smaller priority queue in practice, speeding up queue operations.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Moreover, not inserting all nodes in a graph makes it possible to extend the algorithm to find the shortest path from a single source to the closest of a set of target nodes on infinite graphs or those too large to represent in memory.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Combinations of such techniques may be needed for optimal practical performance on specific problems.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two distance arrays are maintained: *df*[*v*] (distance from s to v) and *db*[*v*] (distance from v to t), initialized to ∞ except *df*[*s*] = 0 and *db*[*t*] = 0.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two priority queues *Qf* and *Qb* hold vertices not yet fully processed, and two sets *Sf* and *Sb* store vertices whose shortest-path distance is finalized in each direction.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A variable μ stores the length of the best full s–t path found so far, initially ∞.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] and symmetrically for the backward search.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A key feature is the stopping condition: once the sum of the current minimum priorities in both queues is at least μ, no yet-unsettled path can improve upon μ.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At this point μ equals the true shortest-path distance δ(*s*,*t*), and the search terminates.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This criterion avoids a common mistake of halting as soon as the two frontiers touch, which may overlook a shorter alternative crossing elsewhere.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because each search only needs to explore roughly half of the search space in typical graphs, the bidirectional method often visits far fewer vertices and relaxes far fewer edges than one-directional Dijkstra on single-pair queries.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In road-network–like graphs the savings can be dramatic, sometimes reducing the explored region from an exponential-size ball to two smaller half-balls.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The method is widely used in point-to-point routing for maps and navigation software and serves as a base for many speed-up techniques such as the ALT, contraction hierarchies, and reach-based routing.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the actual shortest path (not just its distance) is desired, predecessor pointers can be stored in both searches.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When μ is updated through some crossing vertex x, the algorithm records this meeting point and reconstructs the final route as the forward path from s to x concatenated with the backward path from x to t.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Theoretical research shows that an optimized bidirectional approach can be instance-optimal, meaning no correct algorithm can asymptotically relax fewer edges on the same graph instance.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Although Dijkstra's algorithm is optimal for graphs with non-negative edge weights, its practical runtime depends on both data structures and graph properties.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Using a binary heap results in a running time of O((V+E)logV).
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Alternatives such as Fibonacci heaps provide better theoretical bounds but often perform worse in real applications because of large constant factors.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph structure also plays a major role.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Sparse networks, such as road maps, allow Dijkstra's algorithm to operate efficiently since most vertices have low degree.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dense graphs increase relaxations and slow down the process.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of this, modern routing systems often use Dijkstra's algorithm together with preprocessing methods such as A* search, landmark heuristics, or contraction hierarchies, which significantly reduce the search space.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Memory locality is another important factor.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Cache-optimized priority queues and adjacency layouts can reduce latency for large graphs that exceed CPU cache limitations.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of these considerations, most real-world systems use specialized Dijkstra variants tuned for specific graph families and hardware constraints.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As well as simply computing distances and paths, Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to sort vertices by their distances from a given starting vertex.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To achieve this, they use a comparison-based heap whose cost of returning/removing the minimum element from the heap is logarithmic in the number of elements inserted after it rather than in the number of elements in the heap.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When arc weights are small integers (bounded by a parameter C ), specialized queues can be used for increased speed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The first algorithm of this type was Dial's algorithm for graphs with positive integer edge weights, which uses a bucket queue to obtain a running time $O(|E|+|V|C)$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The use of a Van Emde Boas tree as the priority queue brings the complexity to $O(|E|+|V|\log C/\log \log |V|C)$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Another interesting variant based on a combination of a new radix heap and the well-known Fibonacci heap runs in time $O(|E|+|V|{\sqrt {\log C}})$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's original algorithm can be extended with modifications.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, sometimes it is desirable to present solutions which are less than mathematically optimal.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To obtain a ranked list of less-than-optimal solutions, the optimal solution is first calculated.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A single edge appearing in the optimal solution is removed from the graph, and the optimum solution to this new graph is calculated.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Each edge of the original solution is suppressed in turn and a new shortest-path calculated.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The secondary solutions are then ranked and presented after the first optimal solution.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is usually the working principle behind link-state routing protocols.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Unlike Dijkstra's algorithm, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used on graphs with negative edge weights, as long as the graph contains no negative cycle reachable from the source vertex *s*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The presence of such cycles means that no shortest path can be found, since the label becomes lower each time the cycle is traversed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] (This statement assumes that a "path" is allowed to repeat vertices.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In graph theory that is normally not allowed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In theoretical computer science it often is allowed.) It is possible to adapt Dijkstra's algorithm to handle negative weights by combining it with the Bellman-Ford algorithm (to remove negative edges and detect negative cycles): Johnson's algorithm.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The A* algorithm is a generalization of Dijkstra's algorithm that reduces the size of the subgraph that must be explored, if additional information is available that provides a lower bound on the distance to the target.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The process that underlies Dijkstra's algorithm is similar to the greedy process used in Prim's algorithm.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's purpose is to find a minimum spanning tree that connects all nodes in the graph; Dijkstra is concerned with only two nodes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's does not evaluate the total weight of the path from the starting node, only the individual edges.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Breadth-first search can be viewed as a special-case of Dijkstra's algorithm on unweighted graphs, where the priority queue degenerates into a FIFO queue.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The fast marching method can be viewed as a continuous version of Dijkstra's algorithm which computes the geodesic distance on a triangle mesh.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:yen-k-shortest/dijkstra-s-algorithm] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's principle of optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] The ***k* shortest path routing** problem is a generalization of the shortest path routing problem in a given network.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] It asks not only about a shortest path but also about next *k−1* shortest paths (which may be longer than the shortest path).
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] A variation of the problem is the loopless *k* shortest paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Finding *k* shortest paths is possible by extending Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman-Ford algorithm.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Since 1957, many papers have been published on the *k* shortest path routing problem.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Most of the fundamental works were done between 1960s and 2001.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Since then, most of the research has been on the problem's applications and its variants.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In 2010, Michael Günther et al. published a book on *Symbolic calculation of*k*-shortest paths and related measures with the stochastic process algebra tool CASPA*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm can be generalized to find the *k* shortest paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] There are two main variations of the *k* shortest path routing problem.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In one variation, paths are allowed to visit the same node more than once, thus creating loops.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In another variation, paths are required to be simple and loopless.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] The loopy version is solvable using Eppstein's algorithm and the loopless variation is solvable by Yen's algorithm.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In this variant, the problem is simplified by not requiring paths to be loopless.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Fox in 1975 in which the *k*-shortest paths are determined in *O*(*m* + *kn* log *n*) asymptotic time complexity (using big *O* notation).
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In 1998, David Eppstein reported an approach that maintains an asymptotic complexity of *O*(*m* + *n* log *n* + *k*) by computing an implicit representation of the paths, each of which can be output in *O*(*n*) extra time.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In 2015, Akiba *et al.* devised an indexing method as a significantly faster alternative for Eppstein's algorithm, in which a data structure called an index is constructed from a graph and then top-*k* distances between arbitrary pairs of vertices can be rapidly obtained.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In the loopless variant, the paths are forbidden to contain loops, which adds an additional level of complexity.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] It can be solved using Yen's algorithm to find the lengths of all shortest paths from a fixed node to all other nodes in an *n*-node non negative-distance network, a technique requiring only 2*n*2 additions and *n*2 comparison, fewer than other available shortest path algorithms need.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] The running time complexity is pseudo-polynomial, being *O*(*kn*(*m* + *n* log *n*)) (where *m* and *n* represent the number of edges and vertices, respectively).
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In 2007, John Hershberger and Subhash Suri proposed a replacement paths algorithm, a more efficient implementation of Lawler's and Yen's algorithm with *O*(*n*) improvement in time for a large number of graphs, but not all of them (therefore not changing the asymptotic bound of Yen's algorithm).
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] The following example makes use of Yen's model to find *k* shortest paths between communicating end nodes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] That is, it finds a shortest path, second shortest path, etc. up to the Kth shortest path.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Another example is the use of *k* shortest paths algorithm to track multiple objects.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] The technique implements a multiple object tracker based on the *k* shortest paths routing algorithm.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] A set of probabilistic occupancy maps is used as input.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] The complete details can be found at "Computer Vision Laboratory – CVLAB".
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Another use of *k* shortest paths algorithms is to design a transit network that enhances passengers' experience in public transportation systems.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Such an example of a transit network can be constructed by putting traveling time under consideration.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] In addition to traveling time, other conditions may be taken depending upon economical and geographical limitations.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Despite variations in parameters, the *k* shortest path algorithms finds the most optimal solutions that satisfies almost all user needs.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Such applications of *k* shortest path algorithms are becoming common, recently Xu, He, Song, and Chaudhry (2012) studied the *k* shortest path problems in transit network systems.
[src:yen-k-shortest/eppstein-s-algorithm] Cherkassky et al. provide more algorithms and associated evaluations.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **path** in a graph is a finite or infinite sequence of edges which joins a sequence of vertices which, by most definitions, are all distinct (and since the vertices are distinct, so are the edges).
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] A **directed path** (sometimes called **dipath**) in a directed graph is a finite or infinite sequence of edges which joins a sequence of distinct vertices, but with the added restriction that the edges be all directed in the same direction.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] Paths are fundamental concepts of graph theory, described in the introductory sections of most graph theory texts.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] (1990) cover more advanced algorithmic topics concerning paths in graphs.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] ) has a first vertex but no last vertex.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] If there is a finite walk between two *distinct* vertices then there is also a finite trail and a finite path between them.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] Some authors do not require that all vertices of a path be distinct and instead use the term **simple path** to refer to such a path where all vertices are distinct.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] A weighted graph associates a value (*weight*) with every edge in the graph.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] The *weight of a walk* (or trail or path) in a weighted graph is the sum of the weights of the traversed edges.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] Sometimes the words *cost* or *length* are used instead of weight.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] Similarly for a directed trail or a path.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] If there is a finite directed walk between two *distinct* vertices then there is also a finite directed trail and a finite directed path between them.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] A "simple directed path" is a path where all vertices are distinct.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] A weighted directed graph associates a value (*weight*) with every edge in the directed graph.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] The *weight of a directed walk* (or trail or path) in a weighted directed graph is the sum of the weights of the traversed edges.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] Several algorithms exist to find shortest and longest paths in graphs, with the important distinction that the former problem is computationally much easier than the latter.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] Dijkstra's algorithm produces a list of shortest paths from a source vertex to every other vertex in directed and undirected graphs with non-negative edge weights (or no edge weights), whilst the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be applied to directed graphs with negative edge weights.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] The Floyd–Warshall algorithm can be used to find the shortest paths between all pairs of vertices in weighted directed graphs.
[src:yen-k-shortest/path-graph-theory] The **k-path partition** problem is the problem of partitioning a given graph to a smallest collection of vertex-disjoint paths of length at most *k*.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] In graph theory, the **shortest path problem** is the problem of finding a path between two vertices (or nodes) in a graph such that the sum of the weights of its constituent edges is minimized.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the shortest path between two intersections on a road map may be modeled as a special case of the shortest path problem in graphs, where the vertices correspond to intersections and the edges correspond to road segments, each weighted by the length or distance of each segment.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The shortest path problem can be defined for graphs whether undirected, directed, or mixed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The definition for undirected graphs states that every edge can be traversed in either direction.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Directed graphs require that consecutive vertices be connected by an appropriate directed edge.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Two vertices are adjacent when they are both incident to a common edge.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] A path in an undirected graph is a sequence of vertices $P=(v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n})\in V\times V\times \cdots \times V$ such that $v_{i}$ is adjacent to $v_{i+1}$ for $1\leq i<n$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Such a path P is called a path of length $n-1$ from $v_{1}$ to $v_{n}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] These generalizations have significantly more efficient algorithms than the simplistic approach of running a single-pair shortest path algorithm on all relevant pairs of vertices.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Several well-known algorithms exist for solving this problem and its variants.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Additional algorithms and associated evaluations may be found in Cherkassky, Goldberg & Radzik (1996).
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] An algorithm using topological sorting can solve the single-source shortest path problem in time Θ(*E* + *V*) in arbitrarily-weighted directed acyclic graphs.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The following table is taken from Schrijver (2004), with some corrections and additions.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] A green background indicates an asymptotically best bound in the table; *L* is the maximum length (or weight) among all edges, assuming integer edge weights.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Finds a negative cycle or calculates distances to all vertices.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest path problem finds the shortest paths between every pair of vertices v, v' in the graph.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest paths problem for unweighted directed graphs was introduced by Shimbel (1953), who observed that it could be solved by a linear number of matrix multiplications that takes a total time of *O*(*V*4).
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Shortest path algorithms are applied to automatically find directions between physical locations, such as driving directions on web mapping websites like MapQuest or Google Maps.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] For this application fast specialized algorithms are available.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] For example, if vertices represent the states of a puzzle like a Rubik's Cube and each directed edge corresponds to a single move or turn, shortest path algorithms can be used to find a solution that uses the minimum possible number of moves.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] In a networking or telecommunications mindset, this shortest path problem is sometimes called the min-delay path problem and usually tied with a widest path problem.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] For example, the algorithm may seek the shortest (min-delay) widest path, or widest shortest (min-delay) path.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] A more lighthearted application is the games of "six degrees of separation" that try to find the shortest path in graphs like movie stars appearing in the same film.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Other applications, often studied in operations research, include plant and facility layout, robotics, transportation, and VLSI design.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] A road network can be considered as a graph with positive weights.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The nodes represent road junctions and each edge of the graph is associated with a road segment between two junctions.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The weight of an edge may correspond to the length of the associated road segment, the time needed to traverse the segment, or the cost of traversing the segment.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Using directed edges it is also possible to model one-way streets.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Such graphs are special in the sense that some edges are more important than others for long-distance travel (e.g. highways).
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] This property has been formalized using the notion of highway dimension.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] There are a great number of algorithms that exploit this property and are therefore able to compute the shortest path a lot quicker than would be possible on general graphs.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] All of these algorithms work in two phases.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] In the first phase, the graph is preprocessed without knowing the source or target node.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] In this phase, source and target node are known.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The idea is that the road network is static, so the preprocessing phase can be done once and used for a large number of queries on the same road network.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The algorithm with the fastest known query time is called hub labeling and is able to compute shortest path on the road networks of Europe or the US in a fraction of a microsecond.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] For shortest path problems in computational geometry, see Euclidean shortest path.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The shortest multiple disconnected path is a representation of the primitive path network within the framework of Reptation theory.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The widest path problem seeks a path so that the minimum label of any edge is as large as possible.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Other related problems may be classified into the following categories.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Unlike the shortest path problem, which can be solved in polynomial time in graphs without negative cycles, shortest path problems which include additional constraints on the desired solution path are called Constrained Shortest Path First, and are harder to solve.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] One example is the constrained shortest path problem, which attempts to minimize the total cost of the path while at the same time maintaining another metric below a given threshold.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] This makes the problem NP-complete (such problems are not believed to be efficiently solvable for large sets of data, see P = NP problem).
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Another NP-complete example requires a specific set of vertices to be included in the path, which makes the problem similar to the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP).
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The TSP is the problem of finding the shortest path that goes through every vertex exactly once, and returns to the start.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the longest path in a graph is also NP-complete.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The Canadian traveller problem and the stochastic shortest path problem are generalizations where either the graph is not completely known to the mover, changes over time, or where actions (traversals) are probabilistic.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Sometimes, the edges in a graph have personalities: each edge has its own selfish interest.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] An example is a communication network, in which each edge is a computer that possibly belongs to a different person.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Different computers have different transmission speeds, so every edge in the network has a numeric weight equal to the number of milliseconds it takes to transmit a message.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Our goal is to send a message between two points in the network in the shortest time possible.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] If we know the transmission-time of each computer (the weight of each edge), then we can use a standard shortest-paths algorithm.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] If we do not know the transmission times, then we have to ask each computer to tell us its transmission-time.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] But, the computers may be selfish: a computer might tell us that its transmission time is very long, so that we will not bother it with our messages.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] A possible solution to this problem is to use a variant of the VCG mechanism, which gives the computers an incentive to reveal their true weights.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] In some cases, the main goal is not to find the shortest path, but only to detect if the graph contains a negative cycle.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Many problems can be framed as a form of the shortest path for some suitably substituted notions of addition along a path and taking the minimum.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The general approach to these is to consider the two operations to be those of a semiring.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Semiring multiplication is done along the path, and the addition is between paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] This general framework is known as the algebraic path problem.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] Most of the classic shortest-path algorithms (and new ones) can be formulated as solving linear systems over such algebraic structures.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] More recently, an even more general framework for solving these (and much less obviously related problems) has been developed under the banner of valuation algebras.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] In real-life, a transportation network is usually stochastic and time-dependent.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The travel duration on a road segment depends on many factors such as the amount of traffic (origin-destination matrix), road work, weather, accidents and vehicle breakdowns.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] A more realistic model of such a road network is a stochastic time-dependent (STD) network.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] There is no accepted definition of optimal path under uncertainty (that is, in stochastic road networks).
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] It is a controversial subject, despite considerable progress during the past decade.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] One common definition is a path with the minimum expected travel time.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The main advantage of this approach is that it can make use of efficient shortest path algorithms for deterministic networks.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] However, the resulting optimal path may not be reliable, because this approach fails to address travel time variability.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] To tackle this issue, some researchers use travel duration distribution instead of its expected value.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] So, they find the probability distribution of total travel duration using different optimization methods such as dynamic programming and Dijkstra's algorithm .
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] These methods use stochastic optimization, specifically stochastic dynamic programming to find the shortest path in networks with probabilistic arc length.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The terms *travel time reliability* and *travel time variability* are used as opposites in the transportation research literature: the higher the variability, the lower the reliability of predictions.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] To account for variability, researchers have suggested two alternative definitions for an optimal path under uncertainty.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] The *most reliable path* is one that maximizes the probability of arriving on time given a travel time budget.
[src:yen-k-shortest/shortest-path-problem] An *α-reliable path* is one that minimizes the travel time budget required to arrive on time with a given probability.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] In graph theory, **Yen's algorithm** computes single-source *K*-shortest loopless paths for a graph with non-negative edge cost.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Yen in 1971 and employs any shortest path algorithm to find the best path, then proceeds to find *K* − 1 deviations of the best path.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The algorithm can be broken down into two parts: determining the first k-shortest path, $A^{1}$ , and then determining all other *k*-shortest paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] It is assumed that the container A will hold the *k*-shortest path, whereas the container B will hold the potential *k*-shortest paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] To determine $A^{1}$ , the shortest path from the source to the sink, any efficient shortest path algorithm can be used.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] To find the $A^{k}$ , where k ranges from 2 to K , the algorithm assumes that all paths from $A^{1}$ to $A^{k-1}$ have previously been found.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The k iteration can be divided into two processes: finding all the deviations ${A^{k}}_{i}$ and choosing a minimum length path to become $A^{k}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Note that in this iteration, i ranges from 1 to ${Q^{k}}_{k}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The first process can be further subdivided into three operations: choosing the ${R^{k}}_{i}$ , finding ${S^{k}}_{i}$ , and then adding ${A^{k}}_{i}$ to the container B .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The root path, ${R^{k}}_{i}$ , is chosen by finding the subpath in $A^{k-1}$ that follows the first i nodes of $A^{j}$ , where j ranges from 1 to $k-1$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Then, if a path is found, the cost of edge $d_{i(i+1)}$ of $A^{j}$ is set to infinity.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Next, the spur path, ${S^{k}}_{i}$ , is found by computing the shortest path from the spur node, node i , to the sink.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The removal of previous used edges from $(i)$ to $(i+1)$ ensures that the spur path is different. ${A^{k}}_{i}={R^{k}}_{i}+{S^{k}}_{i}$ , the addition of the root path and the spur path, is added to B .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Next, the edges that were removed, i.e. had their cost set to infinity, are restored to their initial values.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The second process determines a suitable path for $A^{k}$ by finding the path in container B with the lowest cost.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] This path is removed from container B and inserted into container A , and the algorithm continues to the next iteration.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The algorithm assumes that the Dijkstra algorithm is used to find the shortest path between two nodes, but any shortest path algorithm can be used in its place.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The example uses Yen's *K*-Shortest Path Algorithm to compute three paths from $(C)$ to $(H)$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is used to calculate the best path from $(C)$ to $(H)$ , which is $(C)-(E)-(F)-(H)$ with cost 5.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] This path is appended to container A and becomes the first *k*-shortest path, $A^{1}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The edge, $(C)-(E)$ , is removed because it coincides with the root path and a path in container A .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The edge, $(E)-(F)$ , is removed because it coincides with the root path and a path in container A .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The edge, $(F)-(H)$ , is removed because it coincides with the root path and a path in container A .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Of the three paths in container B , ${A^{2}}_{2}$ is chosen to become $A^{2}$ because it has the lowest cost of 7.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] This process is continued to the 3rd *k*-shortest path.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] However, within this 3rd iteration, note that some spur paths do not exist.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] To store the edges of the graph, the shortest path list A , and the potential shortest path list B , $N^{2}+KN$ memory addresses are required.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] At worse case, the every node in the graph has an edge to every other node in the graph, thus $N^{2}$ addresses are needed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Only $KN$ addresses are need for both list A and B because at most only K paths will be stored, where it is possible for each path to have N nodes.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The time complexity of Yen's algorithm is dependent on the shortest path algorithm used in the computation of the spur paths, so the Dijkstra algorithm is assumed.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm has a worse case time complexity of $O(N^{2})$ , but using a Fibonacci heap it becomes $O(M+N\log N)$ , where M is the number of edges in the graph.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Since Yen's algorithm makes $Kl$ calls to the Dijkstra in computing the spur paths, where l is the length of spur paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] In a condensed graph, the expected value of l is $O(\log N)$ , while the worst case is N .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] The time complexity becomes $O(KN(M+N\log N))$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Yen's algorithm can be improved by using a heap to store B , the set of potential *k*-shortest paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Using a heap instead of a list will improve the performance of the algorithm, but not the complexity.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] One method to slightly decrease complexity is to skip the nodes where there are non-existent spur paths.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] This case is produced when all the spur paths from a spur node have been used in the previous $A^{k}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Also, if container B has $K-k$ paths of minimum length, in reference to those in container A , then they can be extract and inserted into container A since no shorter paths will be found.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Eugene Lawler proposed a modification to Yen's algorithm in which duplicates path are not calculated as opposed to the original algorithm where they are calculated and then discarded when they are found to be duplicates.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] These duplicates paths result from calculating spur paths of nodes in the root of $A^{k}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] For instance, $A^{k}$ deviates from $A^{k-1}$ at some node $(i)$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Any spur path, ${S^{k}}_{j}$ where $j=0,\ldots ,i$ , that is calculated will be a duplicate because they have already been calculated during the $k-1$ iteration.
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] Therefore, only spur paths for nodes that were on the spur path of $A^{k-1}$ must be calculated, i.e. only ${S^{k}}_{h}$ where h ranges from $(i+1)^{k-1}$ to $(Q_{k})^{k-1}$ .
[src:yen-k-shortest/yen-s-algorithm] To perform this operation for $A^{k}$ , a record is needed to identify the node where $A^{k-1}$ branched from $A^{k-2}$ .
